really exciting collaborative, "What about 
this? What about that? Oh, maybe this." So  

186
00:15:47,840 --> 00:15:54,040
that was a really big part of how we worked also.
Very intensely collaborative sessions to figure  

187
00:15:54,040 --> 00:16:01,360
out what the idea is and getting it sharp enough 
and crispy enough that we could very confidently  

188
00:16:01,360 --> 00:16:06,240
get a yes from David. That he would know exactly 
what it is and what it means and come back. 

189
00:16:06,240 --> 00:16:09,920
It would be what we pictured and it 
would work the way that we hoped so  

190
00:16:09,920 --> 00:16:14,960
that we would keep going and we wouldn't have 
to reverse or go back to the drawing board.

191
00:16:14,960 --> 00:16:19,720
What it sounds like is essentially you're 
trying to maintain the startup way of  

192
00:16:19,720 --> 00:16:24,520
working as the company grows. Everything you're 
describing is how it feels to be at a startup,  

193
00:16:24,520 --> 00:16:28,400
and this is a method to keep 
that. Does that sound right?

194
00:16:28,400 --> 00:16:36,160
That's exactly what became Shape Up, was how do 
we hold onto that as much as possible? I mean,  

195
00:16:36,160 --> 00:16:40,360
one big ingredient, we had an advantage 
also, which was that Jason and David  

196
00:16:40,360 --> 00:16:48,080
hired so deliberately slowly, and this 
is a fortunate side effect of the fact  

197
00:16:48,080 --> 00:16:54,360
that they didn't take investment money.
So there was never that moment of now's the  

198
00:16:54,360 --> 00:17:01,480
moment when we grow. It was always one person. 
And then the organism adapts. One more person.  

199
00:17:02,280 --> 00:17:11,240
And so, this natural way of working, it was 
organically spreading. There were, I think,  

200
00:17:11,240 --> 00:17:20,920
maybe 10 years before we had the first, "Wait a 
minute, what just happened?" That project didn't  

201
00:17:20,920 --> 00:17:28,480
go well, that's not how things normally run.
Of course there were always ups and downs,  

202
00:17:28,480 --> 00:17:35,280
but it was about 10 years later when we had the 
first project. I mean, I remember the project. I  

203
00:17:35,280 --> 00:17:42,200
remember being at the end of... It was at that 
time already, it had been maybe six weeks or  

204
00:17:42,200 --> 00:17:47,360
seven weeks. We hadn't yet completely locked 
the six-week thing that went into Shape Up. 

205
00:17:47,360 --> 00:17:56,040
And I remember we had a review session and 
there was a fairly new person who's doing  

206
00:17:56,040 --> 00:18:01,560
half of the work on that team, and we had the 
review session and it was like instead of,  

207
00:18:01,560 --> 00:18:07,840
"Oh, look, this is about ready to ship." It was 
like, "There are a lot of open questions here." 

208
00:18:07,840 --> 00:18:16,400
"And not only are there a lot of open questions 
here, we're not getting quick answers as we're  

209
00:18:16,400 --> 00:18:21,960
asking." And what we're starting to realize is 
like, "Oh, not only is this not going to ship,  

210
00:18:21,960 --> 00:18:28,880
but we can't even see the end of this."
That was one of those moments where you're like,  

211
00:18:28,880 --> 00:18:35,560
"Oh, this isn't going to automatically, 
organically just keep it spreading as we  

212
00:18:35,560 --> 00:18:39,000
hire forever." You know what I mean? 
We did reach a point where it's like,  

213
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:45,720
"Oh, we're going to have to figure out when this 
goes well, why does it go well and what do we do  

214
00:18:45,720 --> 00:18:51,880
differently and how do we formalize that so it's 
reproducible as we keep onboarding more people?" 

215
00:18:52,600 --> 00:18:58,880
That's actually when Shape Up as a framework 
started. That's when I really started to lean in  

216
00:18:58,880 --> 00:19:03,320
and I took over that responsibility 
of, "Okay, how do I systematize this?"

217
00:19:03,320 --> 00:19:06,320
That's a great segue to let's actually 
talk about how the Shape Up method works.  

218
00:19:06,840 --> 00:19:10,640
Maybe just at a high level, what are the 
core ingredients to the Shape Up method?

219
00:19:10,640 --> 00:19:21,240
There's basically three maybe big things. So, the 
first thing is this notion of we are not going to  

220
00:19:21,240 --> 00:19:30,120
start something unless we can see the end from 
the beginning. So, we're not going to take a  

221
00:19:30,120 --> 00:19:33,680
big concept and then say, "What's the estimate 
for this thing?" We're not going to say, "Oh,  

222
00:19:33,680 --> 00:19:37,440
we need to build a calendar and then do a whole 
bunch of Figma files or write a whole bunch  

223
00:19:37,440 --> 00:19:41,080
of requirements and then ask for an estimate."
We're going to go the other way around and we're  

224
00:19:41,080 --> 00:19:47,600
going to say, "What is our appetite for this? What 
is the maximum amount of time we're willing to go  

225
00:19:47,600 --> 00:19:52,400
before we actually finish something?" And 
we have that startup moment that we talked  

226
00:19:52,400 --> 00:19:57,800
about. That moment of like, "Ah, you know what I 
mean? It works. We got somewhere." At least this,  

227
00:19:57,800 --> 00:20:03,360
if not the whole project, this meaningful 
piece, we can literally walk away from. 

228
00:20:03,360 --> 00:20:09,560
So then what we found was that there was a lot 
of experimentation. We found that six weeks is  

229
00:20:09,560 --> 00:20:15,920
the maximum that we can see into the future 
where we could actually say, "How do we work  

230
00:20:15,920 --> 00:20:20,480
backward and figure out something we could 
build in that six weeks and really land it?" 

231
00:20:21,520 --> 00:20:27,440
That's the first piece. Is working backward 
from the amount of time we actually want to  

232
00:20:27,440 --> 00:20:34,720
spend on something and say, "What can we do? What 
could we shape so that after that amount of time  

233
00:20:34,720 --> 00:20:39,560
we've gotten to somewhere we want to be?"
It's like if you're going to buy a car or  

234
00:20:40,640 --> 00:20:44,320
you're going to buy a house or you're going to 
rent a new flat or whatever, you have to have  

235
00:20:44,320 --> 00:20:51,200
a budget in mind, right? And the budget then is 
how you choose between all kinds of alternatives  

236
00:20:51,200 --> 00:20:58,080
and make a lot of hard choices and trade-offs to 
figure out like, "Well, I want the faster engine,  

237
00:20:59,440 --> 00:21:04,760
but I have to give this up, or I want it to be fun 
to drive, but we also need space for longer road  

238
00:21:04,760 --> 00:21:12,600
trips." You're making all these trade-offs, right?
So, this second piece is this work that we call  

239
00:21:12,600 --> 00:21:19,840
shaping and the shaping work is, how do we 
actually take this fixed amount of time that  

240
00:21:19,840 --> 00:21:28,520
we've given for ourselves and vary the scope? How 
do we come up with a idea, some version of this  

241
00:21:29,040 --> 00:21:34,360
that's going to work in the amount of time 
that the business is interested in spending? 

242
00:21:34,360 --> 00:21:40,200
So, this is those creative sessions that I was 
talking about where we're jumping all over the  

243
00:21:40,200 --> 00:21:45,520
room in front of the whiteboard and getting 
to an idea. And there, the really key thing is  

244
00:21:45,520 --> 00:21:52,560
that we're getting to an idea where we can see 
the idea. We understand why we're doing this. 

245
00:21:52,560 --> 00:21:56,920
We're wrestling with the problem and we're 
wrestling with the solution until we have an idea  

246
00:21:56,920 --> 00:22:04,600
that we can actually say, "This is what we want to 
go build." So it's not just calendar or dashboard  

247
00:22:04,600 --> 00:22:12,400
or newsletter builder, but it's this idea of 
how we're going to tackle this problem about the  

248
00:22:12,400 --> 00:22:19,960
calendar request, right? So that's the shaping.
And then the third piece is when we've actually  

249
00:22:19,960 --> 00:22:29,080
carved out a fixed amount of time, when we've 
shaped a solution that is from a experience  

250
00:22:29,080 --> 00:22:35,320
standpoint, from a functionality standpoint, from 
a technical standpoint, doable and desirable,  

251
00:22:35,320 --> 00:22:41,360
something that we can make happen in that 
amount of time, then we can give it to a team. 

252
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:48,880
We don't have to do the sometimes called scrum, 
the paper shredder. That's where you take an idea  

253
00:22:48,880 --> 00:22:54,080
and then you split it into 100 tickets, right, and 
you hope that it all glues together still after  

254
00:22:54,080 --> 00:23:00,400
you've done that step. We don't want to do that.
Instead, we want to have a whole idea, give it  

255
00:23:00,400 --> 00:23:06,040
to a team so they see the whole, they really 
understand it, right? And then they can come  

256
00:23:06,040 --> 00:23:11,080
up with their tasks and they can figure out 
how to track that and break it into pieces so  

257
00:23:11,080 --> 00:23:16,600
they can actually take more responsibility.
And so what we see is way more engagement,  

258
00:23:16,600 --> 00:23:21,520
especially from the technical team, right? 
Because instead of, "Here's your ticket," or  

259
00:23:21,520 --> 00:23:27,360
"Here's your user story," it's like, "Here's 
the thing you understand, that makes sense,  

260
00:23:27,360 --> 00:23:31,880
and now you're going to have freedom to figure 
out how to actually make this a reality." 

261
00:23:31,880 --> 00:23:36,280
There's going to be a million things 
to solve in the implementation detail,  

262
00:23:36,280 --> 00:23:39,920
and now you have a bunch of fun problems and 
you don't have to keep asking questions to  

263
00:23:39,920 --> 00:23:44,560
other people to understand what this is or 
how do I make a trade off or that thing.

264
00:23:44,560 --> 00:23:47,840
One of the core elements of this, and I 
want to confirm is that you can pick and  

265
00:23:47,840 --> 00:23:53,960
choose these things into your team. You 
don't need to do this wholesale, correct?

266
00:23:53,960 --> 00:23:58,440
You don't need to do any of it. So,  

267
00:23:59,560 --> 00:24:06,080
this is where it helps to look at what's going 
wrong and what are we trying to fix? And then  

268
00:24:06,080 --> 00:24:10,840
what do I want to bring into this, right?
And usually, what I notice is that people,  

269
00:24:10,840 --> 00:24:14,760
they like to start sometimes with, 
"Oh, I want to give the team,  

270
00:24:14,760 --> 00:24:20,720
let's say six weeks and I want to give the team 
more latitude or let's say more creative freedom,  

271
00:24:20,720 --> 00:24:24,200
that they're going to be responsible in this 
six weeks to figure out how to make it happen." 

272
00:24:24,840 --> 00:24:30,080
And usually a lot of the drive for that 
is, "I'm getting tired of having so many  

273
00:24:30,080 --> 00:24:35,400
meetings and rituals and things that are 
not actually working on the problem and  

274
00:24:35,400 --> 00:24:40,160
doing the work." I mean, especially scrum 
teams, they often complain about that. 

275
00:24:40,160 --> 00:24:45,960
So, what they sometimes see in this is like, "Oh, 
I love this idea that the team is just going to be  

276
00:24:45,960 --> 00:24:49,760
cooking for six weeks and they're not going to, 
we're going to meet as needed and we're going to  

277
00:24:49,760 --> 00:24:54,240
workshop things, but we're not going to be busy 
with all these rituals all the time," right? 

278
00:24:54,240 --> 00:25:01,440
Now, the thing that's tricky is that if you 
want that reality of the team happily buzzing  

279
00:25:01,440 --> 00:25:09,120
and humming like some happy bee colony for this 
six weeks, they need to have a lot more clarity  

280
00:25:09,120 --> 00:25:14,760
around what's the thing that we're solving, right?
And so when we start working backward from that,  

281
00:25:14,760 --> 00:25:20,480
then what we see is that, "Oh, well, if we don't 
shape better, then the team isn't going to have  

282
00:25:20,480 --> 00:25:26,160
the clarity that they need to take over that 
responsibility, so they can make choices and make  

283
00:25:26,160 --> 00:25:32,360
decisions and make trade offs so that they can get 
to the end of this thing." And the worst is that  

284
00:25:32,360 --> 00:25:36,880
sometimes see cases where people are like, "Okay, 
we're doing Shape Up. So, you guys are going to  

285
00:25:36,880 --> 00:25:44,280
build the newsletter builder, okay? But you only 
get six weeks to do it. So use your fixed time,  

286
00:25:44,280 --> 00:25:50,520
vary your scope and enjoy your responsibility." 
You know what I mean? Which is just cruel, right? 

287
00:25:50,520 --> 00:25:55,160
Because I think I'll quote Bob Moesta, 
who's been on your show a couple times,  

288
00:25:55,160 --> 00:26:02,840
"You can't put 10 pounds of crap in a five 
pound bag." So, it's a high academic statement  

289
00:26:03,680 --> 00:26:08,560
and we can't just take any project, no matter how 
giant it is, and then throw it at a team and say,  

290
00:26:08,560 --> 00:26:13,400
"Figure it out and ship something meaningful 
in six weeks by cutting away scope," right? 

291
00:26:13,400 --> 00:26:24,560
So, it starts to raise questions about how do 
we actually decide together what this project  

292
00:26:24,560 --> 00:26:29,560
is? Do we actually have clarity around what 
the idea is and what we're going to build?

293
00:26:30,440 --> 00:26:35,160
Let me follow up on a couple of the elements. 
So appetites, I think for any product manager,  

294
00:26:35,160 --> 00:26:41,040
engineer, designer, anyone that has experienced, 
"Okay, we estimate this landing page is going  

295
00:26:41,040 --> 00:26:43,400
to take a couple of weeks. Great, let's 
work on it," and then it ends up being  

296
00:26:43,400 --> 00:26:49,000
six weeks can understand why this makes sense.
It's just like, "This landing page is not that  

297
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:53,720
important to us. Let us just say we will commit 
two weeks to it. We'll do as much as we can in  

298
00:26:53,720 --> 00:26:59,440
two weeks and then we move on. And scope is not 
allowed to go beyond that." Makes total sense.  

299
00:26:59,440 --> 00:27:02,717
This just makes so much sense as you listen 
to this, especially for people that have...

300
00:27:02,717 --> 00:27:06,040
So much sense as you listen to this, especially 
for people that have just fallen into the problems  

301
00:27:06,040 --> 00:27:12,832
of estimates not being accurate. Then there's 
a six-week element and the key there is your,  

302
00:27:13,600 --> 00:27:18,920
and this is counter to maybe two-week sprints 
like Scrum, is that kind of the where this comes?

303
00:27:18,920 --> 00:27:25,160
So, actually, it turns out that the 
six-week is only a maximum and that's  

304
00:27:25,160 --> 00:27:30,160
really where this number does some work for 
us. If we think of six weeks as a maximum,  

305
00:27:30,160 --> 00:27:36,920
that's going to force us to ask some really 
good questions to ourselves about what piece  

306
00:27:36,920 --> 00:27:42,480
of this do we really think we can land? 
Because if you try to say, in six months,  

307
00:27:42,480 --> 00:27:47,560
we're going to ship this thing, you can't get 
your arms around all of the problems that have to  

308
00:27:47,560 --> 00:27:54,640
get solved for an entire six-month chunk of work 
to actually happen. There are so many unknowns,  

309
00:27:54,640 --> 00:27:59,400
there are so many ticking time bombs of things 
that we didn't understand or couldn't foresee,  

310
00:28:00,080 --> 00:28:06,400
but if we set a ceiling at six weeks, we have a 
much better chance of, I think that's the size  

311
00:28:06,400 --> 00:28:11,920
of something where we can actually shape 
it and surface enough unknowns and reveal  

312
00:28:11,920 --> 00:28:17,000
that complexity before we're in the middle of it.
It doesn't mean that we can't use this technique  

313
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:21,880
to do a two-week project, especially if you're 
on a growth team, you don't want to wait six  

314
00:28:21,880 --> 00:28:25,120
weeks or, you know what I mean? You're going 
to have to artificially bundle things together  

315
00:28:25,120 --> 00:28:30,280
to do six weeks. It's like, look, I've got 
something I want to ship in the next week  

316
00:28:30,280 --> 00:28:34,920
and then I've got a thing that might take two 
weeks after that and then a week after that. So,  

317
00:28:35,680 --> 00:28:39,640
it's more a question of what we're trying 
to take on. It's really that upper limit.

318
00:28:39,640 --> 00:28:41,957
Okay. So, it could be a two-week 
cycle and the appetite is-

319
00:28:41,957 --> 00:28:43,000
It could be a two-week thing.

320
00:28:43,000 --> 00:28:45,120
Cool. So, it's like we're going 
to build this new landing page,  

321
00:28:45,120 --> 00:28:48,440
we're going to give it two weeks and 
then do a shaping session on that.

322
00:28:48,440 --> 00:28:54,720
Now, the other side of that is when it 
comes to feature development or building  

323
00:28:54,720 --> 00:29:01,440
something that's going to be needy enough 
to sell, then there's very few things that  

324
00:29:01,440 --> 00:29:07,920
are going to be a substantial value add to 
a product that you can do in two weeks. So,  

325
00:29:07,920 --> 00:29:13,000
then you get into a point where, well now, we're 
just sprinting and we're just taking one bite  

326
00:29:13,000 --> 00:29:17,680
after the other. And then that's where we can 
land in that situation where we feel like, "Ah,  

327
00:29:17,680 --> 00:29:21,680
I can never see the end of this. I just keep going 
back and saying, one more sprint, one more sprint,  

328
00:29:21,680 --> 00:29:26,880
one more sprint." But six weeks is this long 
enough chunk or sometimes, four weeks that the  

329
00:29:26,880 --> 00:29:31,640
question is kind of, what's big enough that we can 
actually get somewhere with this amount of time?

330
00:29:32,520 --> 00:29:36,600
And there's an implied element to this 
that I think is worth highlighting.  

331
00:29:36,600 --> 00:29:41,560
The whole idea is you commit to the 
appetite and if you are not on track  

332
00:29:41,560 --> 00:29:47,960
to hit that instead of extending the 
date you cut in order to still hit it.

333
00:29:47,960 --> 00:29:54,240
This is a tricky one.
So, you're right that it's implied,  

334
00:29:54,240 --> 00:30:00,960
but the thing is, in real life, if you make a 
commitment and you get alignment that we are  

335
00:30:00,960 --> 00:30:06,880
going to spend six weeks of engineering time 
building this thing, if you get to that end  

336
00:30:06,880 --> 00:30:13,560
of that six weeks and something is going wrong, 
it wasn't shaped, we can't see the end of it.  

337
00:30:13,560 --> 00:30:18,520
It's more complicated than we thought. All these 
different things. And by the way, we can also talk  

338
00:30:18,520 --> 00:30:23,800
about why those things happen, but when we get 
in that situation, if we're at the end of the six  

339
00:30:23,800 --> 00:30:31,720
weeks and it's not looking good, we can't just 
cut off what we agreed to that made this thing  

340
00:30:31,720 --> 00:30:36,960
valuable. We can't just cut the scope and say, 
"Oh, well now, we managed to ship inside of six  

341
00:30:36,960 --> 00:30:41,320
weeks." That's going to kill everybody's morale. 
Everyone's going to feel disappointed. We're going  

342
00:30:41,320 --> 00:30:46,080
to feel like this wasn't really worthwhile.
And now, we go into the next cycle with this  

343
00:30:46,920 --> 00:30:52,080
debt feeling that we didn't actually finish 
the thing we were supposed to finish, so now,  

344
00:30:52,080 --> 00:30:57,920
we're like overtime. None of that is good. And 
if we also go the other extreme and just say,  

345
00:30:58,800 --> 00:31:03,720
well, should we say in the book, we had this 
principle at base camp which was this notion  

346
00:31:03,720 --> 00:31:09,560
of the circuit breaker. If a project is not on 
track to actually finish after the six weeks,  

347
00:31:09,560 --> 00:31:17,000
we're just going to cancel it and rethink. 
Almost no teams have the stomach for that,  

348
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:24,720
but the version of that that's more stomachable 
is look, we can't just cancel the project and then  

349
00:31:24,720 --> 00:31:30,560
say, "Let's see what comes next." But what we can 
do is say, "We're not going to keep reinvesting  

350
00:31:30,560 --> 00:31:37,520
in something that we don't understand."
So, let's take this out of build mode and  

351
00:31:37,520 --> 00:31:43,880
bring this back into shaping mode, which might 
mean different people, a different conversation  

352
00:31:43,880 --> 00:31:51,760
asking different questions, doing a different 
kind of work to suss out what is it that's fuzzy  

353
00:31:51,760 --> 00:31:58,200
here? What is it that we couldn't see? What do we 
not understand? How do we get to the clarity that  

354
00:31:58,200 --> 00:32:02,720
we need, so that we can actually say this thing 
is going to happen if we give it another whack.

355
00:32:02,720 --> 00:32:06,520
I love just how real this approach 
is not this theoretical. Okay,  

356
00:32:06,520 --> 00:32:10,080
cool. After six weeks, use just 
the scope and it's all that's cool.

357
00:32:10,080 --> 00:32:11,080
Yeah, you just cut the scope.

358
00:32:11,080 --> 00:32:11,640
Yeah.

359
00:32:11,640 --> 00:32:12,200
No problem.

360
00:32:12,200 --> 00:32:13,520
Shape your gut, put your gut.

361
00:32:13,520 --> 00:32:20,040
I've seen some Shape Up adoptions that looked 
like that by the way, and that's not the way.  

362
00:32:20,800 --> 00:32:24,760
The shaping step is crucial. And what you 
mentioned with your landing page example,  

363
00:32:24,760 --> 00:32:33,160
by the way, it's so seductive because we can 
imagine, oh, Parkinson's law, right? If you give  

364
00:32:33,160 --> 00:32:37,440
me six weeks to do the landing page, I'll find 
a way to use it, but if you give me two weeks,  

365
00:32:37,440 --> 00:32:45,400
then I'll stop after two weeks. But when it 
comes to real product work, where there's some  

