01:06:20,640 --> 01:06:27,440
a little bit more mixed, if they're not all super 
senior, is a simple exercise of at kickoff, take  

728
01:06:27,440 --> 01:06:35,080
whatever was shaped and just draw a grid with nine 
boxes, and give me nine boxes of the nine major  

729
01:06:35,080 --> 01:06:41,200
chunks that you think have to get implemented from 
an implementation standpoint. So translate this  

730
01:06:41,200 --> 01:06:47,480
into nine major scopes of implementation that need 
to somehow happen over the time box. So really,  

731
01:06:47,480 --> 01:06:52,080
really useful exercise to kick things off, 
and we have a lot of teams doing that now. 

732
01:06:52,080 --> 01:06:57,400
If you take six weeks, that's 30 
business days. You divide that by nine,  

733
01:06:57,400 --> 01:07:05,560
it's four days per box. So you're going to get a 
lot of clarity from a quick exercise. And again,  

734
01:07:05,560 --> 01:07:12,640
this is done by the builders. This is a really 
also good exercise for them to notice like, "Oh,  

735
01:07:12,640 --> 01:07:16,200
wait a minute, we think there's too much scope 
here. Even though it seemed reasonable, when we  

736
01:07:16,200 --> 01:07:22,080
put it into nine boxes, it's like, I don't think 
we can do this all." Or it's also a good moment  

737
01:07:22,080 --> 01:07:27,880
where somebody who's more junior might describe 
their implementation approach, and then someone  

738
01:07:27,880 --> 01:07:32,600
who's senior can review that and say, "Actually, 
we've done that before, and we'll run into this  

739
01:07:32,600 --> 01:07:39,040
trouble if we don't use this other thing." So 
those really nice coaching moments can happen.

740
01:07:39,760 --> 01:07:42,880
If you were to try this approach 
and have a shaping session,  

741
01:07:42,880 --> 01:07:47,040
this is a sign you're heading in a good 
direction, is if the output, the team  

742
01:07:47,040 --> 01:07:55,240
that's building it can come up with nine... 
Does it have to be nine? Is six cool, 10 cool?

743
01:07:55,240 --> 01:08:02,680
What I found is if it's more than 10, 
then you just get into ticket land of,  

744
01:08:02,680 --> 01:08:07,120
here's a million things I have to do. You 
know what I mean? If you have 100 things,  

745
01:08:07,120 --> 01:08:10,400
that doesn't tell me anything. 
But if it has to be nine or less.

746
01:08:10,400 --> 01:08:13,200
Nine or less. Okay. Okay, cool.

747
01:08:13,200 --> 01:08:17,600
I actually think... I'm speculating here, but 
the UX designers in your audience will know  

748
01:08:17,600 --> 01:08:23,480
about this rule of seven, plus or minus two. It's 
this cognitive science principle that was found  

749
01:08:23,480 --> 01:08:30,960
about how many things someone can hold in their 
head at once. So this nine is the upper limit of  

750
01:08:30,960 --> 01:08:36,680
seven plus or minus two, and it basically... 
It's like, do we actually have a picture of  

751
01:08:36,680 --> 01:08:40,880
what it means to build this that we can also 
hold in our heads? Can we see the whole castle?

752
01:08:40,880 --> 01:08:44,680
So what I'm hearing is if you're on a, say, 
Agile Scrum team today, if you want to start  

753
01:08:44,680 --> 01:08:50,240
trying this out, it's schedule a shaping 
session, assume it's six weeks to start,  

754
01:08:50,240 --> 01:08:55,440
try to come into it with a framing of 
here's the problem we're trying to solve.  

755
01:08:56,120 --> 01:08:59,240
Is that a good way of thinking about it, 
like the problem we're trying to solve?

756
01:08:59,240 --> 01:09:03,640
Yeah, for sure. The question is what problem are 
we trying to solve, because the shaping work is  

757
01:09:03,640 --> 01:09:08,760
more what are our options for the solution? 
And if the problem is too fuzzy and big,  

758
01:09:08,760 --> 01:09:13,000
if the problem is just calendar, then the 
shaping is going to be this ever-expanding,  

759
01:09:13,000 --> 01:09:16,080
never-ending thing, and we're not 
going to be able to get anywhere.

760
01:09:16,080 --> 01:09:22,320
Yeah. Okay. So you spend three hours, 
maybe six hours in the first session.  

761
01:09:22,320 --> 01:09:26,600
Would you recommend try to keep it to this 
many hours when you're first trying it up?

762
01:09:26,600 --> 01:09:34,800
No, I wouldn't do that. I think the key 
thing is actually if you get to the point  

763
01:09:34,800 --> 01:09:38,440
where you're trying to hold a shaping session 
and you manage to get product and engineering  

764
01:09:38,440 --> 01:09:45,080
into the same room to do it, you are far along. 
You're doing great if you're at that point. Oh,  

765
01:09:46,160 --> 01:09:54,880
so much of the challenge is getting to the point 
of aligning between product and engineering that  

766
01:09:56,400 --> 01:10:01,360
we cannot have projects that are dragging and 
dragging and dragging. We can't keep ending in a  

767
01:10:01,360 --> 01:10:05,960
place where this is the end of a sprint or the end 
of a cycle and we still can't see the end of it,  

768
01:10:06,720 --> 01:10:12,880
or we have to make so many cuts and compromises 
at the last minute that it's not the quality  

769
01:10:12,880 --> 01:10:17,960
of... or it's not really matching what it was 
supposed to be in the first place. When those  

770
01:10:17,960 --> 01:10:22,320
problems are happening or... Also by the 
way, this is surfacing at the exact level. 

771
01:10:22,320 --> 01:10:28,800
Imagine, you're the CPO, you're the CTO, 
and you are supposed to be answering to,  

772
01:10:29,480 --> 01:10:34,160
"How's that work going?"
And it's like, "Well, actually,  

773
01:10:34,160 --> 01:10:40,800
we're working on it. I can just think of a 
couple of times when I needed to go to Jason,  

774
01:10:41,840 --> 01:10:46,600
and he expected me to be making progress on 
something and I had gotten nowhere on it. And that  

775
01:10:46,600 --> 01:10:50,560
feeling when you are with top leadership in the 
room and you don't have a good answer for where  

776
01:10:50,560 --> 01:10:56,160
you are on something is like... Oh, it's brutal, 
right? And then from the CEO's perspective,  

777
01:10:56,160 --> 01:11:02,040
it's like, "Where's the movement? We're running a 
business here. Really, nothing is shipping still?" 

778
01:11:03,760 --> 01:11:10,320
This can't just keep happening. So there's some 
recognition somewhere either at the higher levels  

779
01:11:10,320 --> 01:11:15,400
or within the team of, we don't want to keep 
dragging, we don't want to keep being lost in  

780
01:11:15,400 --> 01:11:24,040
the weeds, and then this can be the activation 
energy. You gather the power to be like, "Okay,  

781
01:11:24,040 --> 01:11:29,200
we actually want to try something different."
And in that case, what I would say is what usually  

782
01:11:29,200 --> 01:11:34,120
works best is, okay, we're going to try a pilot 
project, and what we want to do is, as you said,  

783
01:11:35,280 --> 01:11:39,960
choose a problem that's important enough to all of 
us that we think it's meaningful, it's going to be  

784
01:11:39,960 --> 01:11:46,280
worth trying to do well. And it doesn't have to be 
six weeks. It could be something that is a little  

785
01:11:46,280 --> 01:11:50,800
bit smaller, maybe you feel comfortable taking 
on three week thing for the first time. What's  

786
01:11:50,800 --> 01:11:58,360
important is just matching these things together.
Here's a problem that we actually care about. It's  

787
01:11:58,360 --> 01:12:03,600
timely, something that we would like to be 
shipped soon. It's not so small that we're  

788
01:12:03,600 --> 01:12:09,040
not going to actually learn this new muscle, and 
it's big enough that it's going to feel like we  

789
01:12:09,040 --> 01:12:12,880
really achieved something. So maybe that's going 
to be four weeks, maybe it's going to be six,  

790
01:12:12,880 --> 01:12:22,480
maybe it's three, I don't know. And then getting 
to a place where we wrestle a bit with the problem  

791
01:12:22,480 --> 01:12:27,360
to get the problem narrowed down. We get into our 
shaping session, and then we do our best. Do you  

792
01:12:27,360 --> 01:12:32,800
know what I mean? And usually, what happens too 
is if we have an engineering team that's going  

793
01:12:32,800 --> 01:12:40,320
to become free to do this work for those X number 
of weeks, that's the upper limit on how long we  

794
01:12:40,320 --> 01:12:50,920
can spend to shape, and that's another real 
life thing, is sometimes we talk about if... 

795
01:12:50,920 --> 01:12:56,040
On the one hand there's this universe of never 
ending documents back and forth to get feedback  

796
01:12:56,040 --> 01:12:59,760
and comments, and then on the other 
hand there's like the team is going  

797
01:12:59,760 --> 01:13:05,040
to be available. We're trying to actually do 
this, so actually, we've got a week to shape  

798
01:13:05,040 --> 01:13:09,640
because engineering needs to kick off next week. 
Do you know what I mean? That's a little bit more  

799
01:13:09,640 --> 01:13:16,360
the real scenario when you're actually in this 
aligned world of we want to ship something now.

800
01:13:16,360 --> 01:13:19,360
Yeah, real life constraints. That's 
a really helpful way of telling you  

801
01:13:19,360 --> 01:13:24,720
how much time you have to do this. For 
people that are just like, "I don't know,  

802
01:13:24,720 --> 01:13:28,760
any friends that are using this. It's like 
weird, this way of working. It's not a thing  

803
01:13:28,760 --> 01:13:33,080
I hear about all the time." What can you 
say to them to help them be like, "Okay,  

804
01:13:33,080 --> 01:13:36,920
I should actually give this a try. Here's 
how many people are using it. Here's impact  

805
01:13:36,920 --> 01:13:40,080
that you've seen." Anything you can share 
that would help them get over that hump?

806
01:13:40,080 --> 01:13:51,400
I would say wait until it hurts more. If the 
unfamiliarity is the big problem with it,  

807
01:13:52,400 --> 01:14:00,760
then maybe the things are fine. Because it's 
not like this is the only way. It's more like,  

808
01:14:01,600 --> 01:14:08,920
changing is really hard, and if there's a good 
reason to do it and it's like, look, we've done  

809
01:14:08,920 --> 01:14:14,960
it the old way. We've tried different experiments. 
We've even already churned through a new head of  

810
01:14:14,960 --> 01:14:20,040
product, or we've got a different CTO in and we're 
still having the same problems, then there comes  

811
01:14:20,040 --> 01:14:25,320
a point where it's like, I know that this is 
uncomfortable, and I don't know somebody who's  

812
01:14:25,320 --> 01:14:30,560
done it, but I think we need to try something 
different because we can't continue this way.

813
01:14:30,560 --> 01:14:35,240
That is a great answer. Following that 
same thread, just what are signs that  

814
01:14:35,240 --> 01:14:39,720
it's time to try something? What sort 
of pain do you often see that's like,  

815
01:14:39,720 --> 01:14:43,880
okay, you shouldn't look into this seriously?

816
01:14:43,880 --> 01:14:54,280
There are pains all along the journey. So I think 
the place where it's most obvious is at the end  

817
01:14:54,280 --> 01:14:58,960
of the line when we thought we were going to 
be done and this thing is just dragging and  

818
01:14:58,960 --> 01:15:03,280
dragging and dragging. The teams, we're not 
shipping things. We're running in place. We  

819
01:15:03,280 --> 01:15:09,840
keep going in circles on this like we don't see 
the end. Of course, that's the culmination, but  

820
01:15:09,840 --> 01:15:18,240
there's also a lot of pain points along the way.
So if we go all the way upstream, if we go to the  

821
01:15:18,240 --> 01:15:24,160
source of a project, sales talk to a customer... 
You know what I mean? Or sales talk to a lead,  

822
01:15:24,160 --> 01:15:29,640
and they have this idea of this thing we 
need to build, or the CEO had this idea in  

823
01:15:29,640 --> 01:15:33,280
the shower the other day, or the product team 
did a whole bunch of research and they have a  

824
01:15:33,280 --> 01:15:36,640
big case for why this is the thing that's 
important to build next. Whatever it is,  

825
01:15:36,640 --> 01:15:43,840
there's a source from the business perspective 
of this is the thing we should do next. 

826
01:15:44,920 --> 01:15:49,000
If we just say dashboard and we don't negotiate 
what that means, if we just say calendar and we  

827
01:15:49,000 --> 01:16:00,000
don't negotiate what that actually is, then 
what do we experience? This fuzzy thing where  

828
01:16:00,960 --> 01:16:07,320
it's really hard to get to a conclusive answer 
about, yeah, that's what we need to go do. It's  

829
01:16:07,320 --> 01:16:15,000
like the ever expanding blob. So if you've felt 
that before, that's already a first pain. And  

830
01:16:15,000 --> 01:16:18,600
then of course, where does it go from there? So 
we say calendar, so we don't know what it means,  

831
01:16:18,600 --> 01:16:24,560
but we say calendar, so now we give it to product 
and we've either got a whole bunch of Figma files  

832
01:16:24,560 --> 01:16:32,120
or we have the PRD with a million requirements 
about what a great calendar is. Of course,  

833
01:16:32,120 --> 01:16:36,040
I don't want to be cruel to the people who 
are putting their hearts into that work,  

834
01:16:36,040 --> 01:16:42,840
because the Figma file is beautiful. It's just 
coming a little early. And the PRD is full of  

835
01:16:42,840 --> 01:16:48,240
a lot of true things that are probably really 
important for decision-making in the project,  

836
01:16:48,240 --> 01:16:55,480
but the way that it's packaged at that moment 
isn't something that gets absorbed. You write this  

837
01:16:55,480 --> 01:17:01,960
document and I'm sorry, who actually reads it? You 
know what I mean? I know it's painful, but it's  

838
01:17:01,960 --> 01:17:09,240
like that. And then even when we try to read it, 
because it wasn't shaped and we didn't get down  

839
01:17:09,240 --> 01:17:16,080
to it's this, it's that, it's that, and that's how 
it works, it's hard to walk away from reading that  

840
01:17:16,080 --> 01:17:22,200
and have anything that's in your head as, this is 
what we're going to go build. It's like a million  

841
01:17:22,200 --> 01:17:30,160
puzzle pieces that you're going to have to solve. 
So what we see is either there's the Figma file  

842
01:17:30,160 --> 01:17:37,600
and then there's the pushback from engineers. 
There's the PRD, but then it's like, okay,  

843
01:17:37,600 --> 01:17:42,120
but we still don't actually know what to build.
There's all those things where, instead of moving  

844
01:17:42,120 --> 01:17:45,920
forward, there's more and more questions, more 
and more pushback, more and more going back to  

845
01:17:45,920 --> 01:17:52,080
the drawing board. So that's another big indicator 
that something is going wrong. And then when we're  

846
01:17:52,080 --> 01:17:57,440
in the building and we thought we knew what 
we agreed to, we thought we all said, "Yeah,  

847
01:17:57,440 --> 01:18:02,120
this is what we want to go make," and it's 
just more and more questions coming out. More  

848
01:18:02,120 --> 01:18:07,800
and more unexpected complexity, things that we 
didn't anticipate, and it just doesn't feel like  

849
01:18:07,800 --> 01:18:14,080
we're getting warmer and coming closer. It just 
feels like it's getting harder and harder. Those  

850
01:18:14,080 --> 01:18:21,440
are all the signs that whatever process you use, 
that there's a lack of clear shaping and there's  

851
01:18:21,440 --> 01:18:26,640
a lack of clear framing because there's a lack 
of clarity around what it is that we're doing.

852
01:18:26,640 --> 01:18:29,080
Before we started recording, you made 
this interesting point that there's  

853
01:18:29,080 --> 01:18:33,280
always talk of feature factories 
and that rarely are they actually  

854
01:18:33,280 --> 01:18:38,320
efficient factories. They don't 
actually work. Talk about that.

855
01:18:38,320 --> 01:18:44,360
Yeah. Well, I understand what the feature factory 
critique is supposed to be. It's actually to  

856
01:18:44,360 --> 01:18:50,320
the framing point of we're not negotiating the 
value and the outcome we're trying to get from  

857
01:18:50,320 --> 01:18:56,040
something. We're just taking it and building it. 
And then of course, in the end, according to the  

858
01:18:56,040 --> 01:19:00,720
feature factory critique, we just built it because 
somebody said we should build it, and then people  

859
01:19:00,720 --> 01:19:05,040
didn't use it and didn't value it, and the product 
is just getting bloated. The thing is that,  

860
01:19:05,760 --> 01:19:11,120
I would say if you have a feature factory, meaning 
you're continually cranking out features, you're  

861
01:19:11,120 --> 01:19:16,680
probably quite healthy. All you need to do is feed 
a different input to the beginning of the factory. 

862
01:19:18,160 --> 01:19:23,960
What most teams are struggling with is that 
they don't have predictable repeatable shipping  

863
01:19:23,960 --> 01:19:30,360
of things. At least from my experience, 
the bigger really widespread struggle is,  

864
01:19:30,360 --> 01:19:36,360
stuff isn't moving, it's dragging. I can't see 
the end. I'm losing my... I'm feeling burned  

865
01:19:36,360 --> 01:19:41,040
out. You know what I mean? It's not exciting 
to work on this anymore, all that a thing.

866
01:19:41,040 --> 01:19:46,160
Maybe last question here is what's the 
sweet spot stage for a company to start  

867
01:19:46,160 --> 01:19:49,720
using Shape Up? You basically worked in 
this way from the very beginning when  

868
01:19:49,720 --> 01:19:53,520
it was just three people. What do you 
find... Should startups that are just  

869
01:19:53,520 --> 01:19:57,880
starting out start working in this way, 
or do you find it's more useful later on?

870
01:19:57,880 --> 01:20:03,120
We didn't formalize it until we had to, and there 
was a long time where there wasn't a fixed length  

871
01:20:03,120 --> 01:20:08,520
for projects. There was just an understanding of 
the urgency and a feeling of what too long felt  

872
01:20:08,520 --> 01:20:15,160
like. And it didn't actually click into, oh, 
this is a cycle length and this is six weeks,  

873
01:20:15,160 --> 01:20:21,360
and then we pause, and this is who comes together 
to make the decision of what's the next project,  

874
01:20:21,360 --> 01:20:25,920
and here's who is mainly doing the shape. You 
know what I mean? All that stuff didn't get solved  

875
01:20:25,920 --> 01:20:30,960
until we had reached a certain size. Usually, the 
main tipping point if we start from smaller to big  

876
01:20:30,960 --> 01:20:37,840
is there's a phase when the founders are still 
involved in everything, and so it doesn't matter  

877
01:20:37,840 --> 01:20:43,080
what your process is, it's going to be fine.
But then you start to hire the first other  

878
01:20:43,080 --> 01:20:47,800
people and then for the first time you try to 
delegate some of those things and the founders  

879
01:20:47,800 --> 01:20:52,560
try to be less involved, and that's often where 
a lot of these problems start to appear. And the  

880
01:20:52,560 --> 01:20:57,720
founders start to ask themselves like, "We used 
to be fast, and now we hired people because we  

881
01:20:57,720 --> 01:21:00,510
needed to scale, but now we're slow. So how 
do we be fast again? Because we know what-

882
01:21:00,510 --> 01:21:05,600
... well. So like, "How will we be fast again?" 
Because we know what it's like. If we just got  

883
01:21:05,600 --> 01:21:10,880
back in there as founders and got our hands 
dirty, like we could make this go. But how do  

884
01:21:10,880 --> 01:21:18,560
I get the people that we've brought in to make 
these trade-offs and make these decisions and  

885
01:21:18,560 --> 01:21:22,960
how do I get the work to flow again? So that's 
something that we definitely see there. So that's  

886
01:21:22,960 --> 01:21:28,800
a really good moment. I'm onboarding new people. I 
don't know what to tell them how to work. I don't  

887
01:21:28,800 --> 01:21:34,120
want to introduce a bunch of scrum rituals. Just 
winging it on Kanban isn't working, because they  

888
01:21:34,120 --> 01:21:38,040
don't have enough clarity around what to go after. 
So I have to babysit them all the time. You know  

889
01:21:38,040 --> 01:21:45,240
what I mean? Like these kinds of things.
There is another extreme, which is I...  

890
01:21:46,840 --> 01:21:57,840
We've already gone past that. We've been scrum or 
whatever for years. The company has been growing,  

891
01:21:57,840 --> 01:22:02,760
like revenue is coming in, like sales is doing 
their job, like things are running. But man,  

892
01:22:02,760 --> 01:22:09,800
nothing is getting out the door. And we're years 
in and we have an entrenched development. We  

893
01:22:09,800 --> 01:22:14,680
have like an entrenched engineering team, 
which is a wall away from an entrenched  

894
01:22:14,680 --> 01:22:19,320
product team and everybody's apart. And 
this thing is like, we're like stuck. 

895
01:22:19,320 --> 01:22:23,880
And that is more where there's going to be 
some tensions that are starting to appear  

896
01:22:23,880 --> 01:22:27,440
at the executive level. There's going to be some 
finger pointing. There's going to be some like,  

897
01:22:27,440 --> 01:22:31,400
"Why isn't this moving? Why isn't this happening? 
How can we be spending so much money in all these  

898
01:22:31,400 --> 01:22:37,120
engineers and we don't have anything to show 
for it?" And that's a point where there can  

899
01:22:37,120 --> 01:22:42,840
be kind of a... Some hard conversations need 
to start happening about, "How do we actually  

900
01:22:42,840 --> 01:22:48,080
start to negotiate around how we spend time?" 
And we can't just have endless refactorings  

901
01:22:48,080 --> 01:22:54,520
and infrastructure projects, but we need to be 
actually building things that we can sell again.

902
01:22:54,520 --> 01:22:56,160
What an idea.

903
01:22:56,160 --> 01:23:03,200
Yeah. You know? But it can... There are a lot of 
engineering orgs that have been standing around  

904
01:23:03,200 --> 01:23:08,760
for a while and it's all refactoring all day 
and tech debt and stuff like that. And there's  

905
